TITLE: 'Where is humanity?' ask the helpless doctors of Ethiopia's embattled Tigray region
SUMMARY: Civil war has blockaded the country's northern region and decimated a hospital system that serves nearly 7 million people. Without basic supplies, power and medicine, thousands are needlessly dying.

TITLE: The U.K. prime minister fired her finance chief, a sign she may change course on taxes
SUMMARY: In a move designed to calm financial markets and her own conservative party, Prime Minister Liz Truss canceled planned tax cuts for the wealthy and fired her finance minister.

TITLE: LA City Council scandal highlights the racial fault lines of a very diverse city
SUMMARY: NPR's A Martinez talks to USC professor Manuel Pastor and Erika Smith of the <em>Los Angeles Times

TITLE: Fishermen face felony charges over a cheating scandal at an Ohio tournament
SUMMARY: A grand jury indicted the fishing team on charges of cheating, attempted grand theft and possessing criminal tools. They had stood to win nearly $30,000.

TITLE: Kroger and Albertsons plan merger to combine 2 largest supermarket chains
SUMMARY: The $25-billion deal is likely to draw intense scrutiny from federal regulators and critics as it would form a new supermarket mega giant at a time of soaring food costs.

TITLE: Brain cells in a lab dish learn to play Pong — and offer a window onto intelligence
SUMMARY: A dish of brain cells learned to play the 1970s video game Pong. The research could help computers become more intelligent

TITLE: Florida agriculture has been slammed by Hurricane Ian
SUMMARY: Agriculture is a major industry in Florida and Hurricane Ian destroyed farms, killed livestock and toppled citrus trees. Farmers have faced challenges before and vow to come out stronger.

TITLE: Ukrainians grieve for an 11-year-old girl killed by a Russian missile
SUMMARY: A neighbor recalls the girl saying in her final moments, "Why did this happen to me? I didn't do anything bad to them."

TITLE: This Nigerian city has a high birth rate of twins — and no one is sure why
SUMMARY: Twins appear to be unusually abundant in Nigeria's southwestern city of Igbo-Ora. For the past 12 years, the community has organized an annual festival to celebrate twins.

TITLE: About a third of people call doctors by their first names, a new study shows
SUMMARY: Researchers at the Mayo Clinic evaluated about 90,000 messages between doctors and their patients and found differences in patients' responses based on the doctor's gender and area of practice

TITLE: German students break the world record for fastest accelerating electric car — again
SUMMARY: The electric racing car, built by 20 University of Stuttgart students known as the GreenTeam, can go from 0 to about 62 miles per hour in just 1.461 seconds.

TITLE: Animal populations shrunk an average of 69% over the last half-century, a report says
SUMMARY: A new report from the World Wildlife Fund and the Zoological Society of London analyzed years of data on wildlife populations across the world and found a downward trend in the Earth's biodiversity.

TITLE: 'Water batteries' could store solar and wind power for when it's needed
SUMMARY: San Diego has an ambitious plan to store renewable energy, using extra solar power to pump water up a mountain. This old-style "water battery" technology could be set for a revival.

TITLE: How quotation marks turned a story about a clerical error into one about voter fraud
SUMMARY: The Colorado election officials accidentally mailed postcards about voting registration to non-citizens who were not eligible to vote. On Twitter, stories about the mistake have turned conspiratorial.

TITLE: A pair of Levi's that sold for $76K reflects anti-Chinese sentiment of 19th century
SUMMARY: A pocket on the 1880s-era pair of jeans says, "The only kind made by white labor."
